	<title>Exercises: A Linear Map from a Matrix</title>
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the statements below indicate if it is true or false.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing a linear function <latex>L\from \RNr[7]\to \RNr[5]</latex> has size <latex>(5,7)</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True!</para></answer>
				<solution>
					<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[n]\to \RNr[m]</latex> is a linear function, then the matrix representing <latex>L</latex> has <latex>m</latex> rows (horizontal), and <latex>n</latex> columns (vertical). Therefore this matrix has size <latex>(m,n)</latex>.</para>
					<para>In the question at hand, this means that <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> has size <latex>(5,7)</latex>.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing a linear function <latex>L\from \RNr[7]\to \RNr[5]</latex> has size <latex>(7,5)</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>False!</para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>See the solution of the previous part.</para></solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing a linear function <latex>L\from \RNr[7]\to \RNr[5]</latex> is square shaped with <latex>7</latex> rows and <latex>7</latex> columns.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>False!</para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>See the solution of the previous parts.</para></solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The linear transformation <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[3]</latex> represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
				A =
					\left[
					\begin{array}{rr}
					4 & 1 \\
					0 & 3 \\
					1 & 2
					\end{array}
					\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>has domain <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> and target <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True.</para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The linear transformation <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[3]</latex> represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
				A =
					\left[
					\begin{array}{rr}
					4 & 1 \\
					0 & 3 \\
					1 & 2
					\end{array}
					\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>has domain <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> and target <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>False.</para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>The linear transformation <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[3]</latex> represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
				A =
					\left[
					\begin{array}{rr}
					4 & 1 \\
					0 & 3 \\
					1 & 2
					\end{array}
					\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>transforms the vector <latex>\Vect{a}:=(1,-1)</latex> into the vector <latex>(3,-3,-1)</latex>.</para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True.</para></answer>
				<solution>
					<para>We compute</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
\aligned
L(\Vect{a})\ &\ 
\left[
					\begin{array}{rr}
					4 & 1 \\
					0 & 3 \\
					1 & 2
					\end{array}
					\right] \left[\begin{array}{r} 1 \\ -1 \end{array}\right] \\
& \left[\begin{array}{r} 3 \\ -3 \\ -1 \end{array}\right]
\endaligned
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Therefore the statement in question is true.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para>For each of the statements below indicate if it is true or false.</para>
		</problem>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Then <latex>L(1,0) = (4,2)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True!</para></answer>
				<solution>
					<para>We compute</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
L(1,0)\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
1 \\ 0
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
4 \\ 2
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Therefore the statement in question is true.</para>
					<para>Note that <latex>(1,0)=\StdBss{1}</latex> is the first standard basis vector of <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>. Therefore the matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> representing <latex>L</latex> transforms it into the first column vector of <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Then <latex>L(1,0) = (4,-1)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>False!</para></answer>
				<solution.hint><para>Review the solution of part a) and, in particular, the comment at its end.</para></solution.hint>
				<solution>
					<para>We compute</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
L(1,0)\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
1 \\ 0
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
4 \\ 2
\end{array}
\right] \neq
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
4 \\ -1
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Therefore the statement in question is false.</para>
					<para>Quicker: <latex>L(\StdBss{1})</latex> is the first column vector of the representing matrix <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>. So we see by comparison of the proposed vector <latex>(4,-1)</latex> with the first column vector of <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> that the statement in question is false.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Then <latex>L(1,0) = (-1,6)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>False!</para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Then <latex>L(1,1) = (3,8)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True!</para></answer>
				<solution>
					<para>We compute</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>
							<![CDATA[
L(1,0)\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
1 \\ 1
\end{array}
\right]\ =\ 
\left[
\begin{array}{r}
3 \\ 8
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
						</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>Therefore the statement in question is true.</para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		<part>
			<problem>
				<para>If <latex>L\from \RNr[2]\to \RNr[2]</latex> is represented by the matrix</para>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A =
\left[
\begin{array}{rr}
4 & -1 \\
2 & 6
\end{array}
\right]
]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
				<para>Then <latex>L(0,1) = (-1,6)</latex></para>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer><para>True!</para></answer>
			</approach>
		</part>
	</exercise>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
	<exercise>
		<problem>
			<para> For the matrices <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> below find the coordinate description of the corresponding linear map.</para>
		</problem>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<math.display><latex>L\from \RNr[3] \longrightarrow \RNr,\quad L(x,y,z) = -2x + y</latex></math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>As <latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex>  is a matrix of size <latex>(1,3)</latex>, the linear transfomration represented by it is a map <latex>L\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr</latex>. The effect of <latex>L</latex> on a vector <latex>\Vect{x}=(x,y,z)</latex> of <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> is given by</para>
					
					<computation>
						<left>L(\Vect{x})</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>\Mtrx{A}\cdot \Vect{x}</right>
						<left>L(x,y,z)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
\left[\begin{array}{rrr}
-2 & 1 & 0
\end{array}\right] \cdot 
\left[\begin{array}{r}
x \\ y \\ z
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							[-2x + y]
						</right>
					</computation>
					
					<para>Therefore,</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>L\from \RNr[3] \longrightarrow \RNr,\quad L(x,y,z) = -2x + y</latex>
					</math.display>
					
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A = \left[\begin{array}{r}
3 \\ -1 \\ \pi \\ 4
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> determines the linear map <latex>T\from \RNr \to \RNr[4]</latex> with</para>
					<computation>
						<left>T(x)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(3x, -x , \pi x , 4x )</right>
					</computation>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The given matrix has size <latex>(4,1)</latex>. So it represents a linear map</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>L\from \RNr[1] \longrightarrow \RNr[4]</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>To find <latex>L(t)</latex> for a number <latex>t</latex> in <latex>\RNr[1]</latex> we compute</para>
					<computation>
						<left>L(t)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
\left[\begin{array}{r}
3 \\ -1 \\ \pi \\ 4
\end{array}\right] [t]
					]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
\left[\begin{array}{r}
3t \\ -t \\ \pi\cdot t \\ 4t
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
					<para>Therefore <latex>L(t) = (3t,-t,\pi\cdot t,4t)</latex></para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
A = \left[\begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> determines the linear map <latex>U\from \RNr[2] \to \RNr[2]</latex> with</para>
					<computation>
						<left>U(x,y)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>(ax + by, cx+dy)</right>
					</computation>
				</answer>
				<solution>
					<para>The given matrix has size <latex>(2,2)</latex>. So it represents a linear map</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>T\from \RNr[2] \longrightarrow \RNr[2].</latex>
					</math.display>
					<para>To find its transformation effect on a vector <latex>(u,v)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>, we compute</para>
					<computation>
						<left>L(u,v)</left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
\left[\begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\
c & d
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{c}
u \\ v
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
						</right>
						<left></left>
						<center>=</center>
						<right>
							<![CDATA[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
au + bv \\
cu + dv
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
						</right>
					</computation>
					<para>Therefore, <latex>T(u,v) = (au+bv,cu+dv)</latex></para>
				</solution>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
		<part>
			<problem>
				<math.display>
					<latex>
						<![CDATA[
\Mtrx{A} = \left[\begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & -1 \\
1 & 2 & -3 \\
1 & 0 & 1
\end{array}\right]
					]]>
					</latex>
				</math.display>
			</problem>
			<approach>
				<answer>
					<para><latex>\Mtrx{A}</latex> represents a linear map <latex>L\from \RNr[3]\to \RNr[3]</latex>. It transforms a vector <latex>(x,y,z)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex> into</para>
					<math.display>
						<latex>L(x,y,z) = (2x+y-z,x+2y-3z,x+z)</latex>
					</math.display>
				</answer>
				<solution.hint>
					<para>Review the solution of the previous parts of this problem.</para>
				</solution.hint>
			</approach>
		</part>
		
